To simplify \(\frac{3+\sqrt{90}}{3}\):

1. Factor \(\sqrt{90}=\sqrt{9\cdot 10}=3\sqrt{10}\).  
2. Then  
   \[
     \frac{3+\sqrt{90}}{3}
     =\frac{3+3\sqrt{10}}{3}
     =\frac{3(1+\sqrt{10})}{3}
     =1+\sqrt{10}.
   \]

Answer: \(1+\sqrt{10}\).

First, pull out perfect squares from under the radical:

\[
\sqrt{\frac{96\,x^7}{121}}
=\frac{1}{11}\,\sqrt{96\,x^7}
=\frac{1}{11}\,\sqrt{16\cdot 6\cdot x^6\cdot x}
=\frac{1}{11}\,(4\,x^3)\sqrt{6x}
=\frac{4x^3\sqrt{6x}}{11}.
\]

Answer: \(\displaystyle \frac{4x^3\sqrt{6x}}{11}.\)

First factor inside the radical:
\[
\sqrt{\frac{300\,m^5}{64}}
=\frac{1}{8}\sqrt{300\,m^5}
=\frac{1}{8}\sqrt{300\,m^4\cdot m}
=\frac{m^2}{8}\,\sqrt{300\,m}.
\]
Since \(300=100\cdot3\),
\[
\frac{m^2}{8}\sqrt{300\,m}
=\frac{m^2}{8}\cdot10\sqrt{3m}
=\frac{10m^2}{8}\sqrt{3m}
=\frac{5m^2}{4}\sqrt{3m}.
\] 
Answer: \(\displaystyle \frac{5m^2}{4}\sqrt{3m}.\)

First pull out all perfect squares from under the radical:

\[
\sqrt{\frac{28\,p^7}{q^2}}
=\frac{\sqrt{28}\,\sqrt{p^7}}{\sqrt{q^2}}
=\frac{\sqrt{4\cdot7}\;\sqrt{p^6}\;\sqrt p}{|q|}
=\frac{2\sqrt7\;p^3\;\sqrt p}{|q|}
=\frac{2p^3\sqrt{7p}}{|q|}.
\]

If you assume \(q>0\), you can drop the absolute‐value and write

\[
\boxed{\frac{2\,p^3\sqrt{7p}}{q}}.
\]
